London mr. John Loyd
I have before mee yd. of 16 past, I observe that you had receaved the tykes, & that you
was proftened 5 p a g. less for the ¼ 3 seales, then they stand you in. I hope better
things, for itt is imposible to buy them here for lest mony, yeasterdag I had severnes
syhe maeckers, & bought some, butt thy generall compleaire, that they can not live, &
that yearnes is a rising, so pray make the best of itt to keep trade in beeng. wee have
now examined yd. yearne, & wee finde that the white is not fitt for tykes, itt beeng
made up with a blew stuff, so that I doubt I must seld that for some other ise
other wise the bundells, & browne yarne is well ordered, yett I have sold itt upon condition
that they shall aye with one bindell of white, if they can gett out the blew, then itt
shall be sold for 24 p a bos, the browne is sold & delivered 100 bos att 20½ and
the bruynswip att ƒ4:10 the bundell, to be payd with tykes, att the ordinary banter rate
which is ½ 2 seales att ƒ7-

mij last ts you was on the 4 sur. sence non from you onely yd bill of 27 past en mee att
vos for £400- att 35„6 which I supose y for my acctt haveing no advise from you, yett shall
accept itt, butt for then future failen not to give advise, when you draw in mee, pray be vere
carefull in buying the spanissh cloathes, fors wee loose severall customens by selling them
that are en handes, as amonghst others haptined this day, & I feare to gett a badd name
by them, avoid all extravagancy in cullours & misture, & lett the browne be exacetely to the
and ensteed of 2 a 3 drap cullours take 4 butt under 8 p a yds pray once a gaine do yd best.
dispatch the silver marckes desired, & besides them you must bespecke 5 more broad liste
towards the latter end of may, provide also 10 pack whites more 173.5 E yeallow, &
5.WW red marckes as best you can have them, butt be not to hasty if you thincks
to have them either better, or cheaper. I would faire have a bale of northaers all
dray cullours M:5 of about 4ƒ ayd raw, & 5 of about 5 p a yd raw, & where as Isupise
you may finde better pattarnes for them with you, so pray be vere carefull to send somes
lovely patt. to the north, to have a curious bale of draps, to serve to putt off all the
aest, & depend here on, & upon yd expeditune

Londen m. Edmund Warner
I have before mee yd of 17 past, my thanckes for accepting my bills. all the packetts are
will arrived in 2 tume att newpoorte to N. 20 inelus so that I hope you will receave them
vere speedly, the stodin goods that are brought in good condition againe follow in a particeler
packett N nept mestengen, I observe what you say of the measure, touley I have
alwayes much ado about itt, & yett the work women will stand upon an & rather give their
& a pennie cheaper, then to loose ⅓ as tley de pretend, though itt be osten disputable yett
shall endeavour to comply with yd desire, as also to gett abatement off the numbers
mentioned, for by them I know alwayes whoes makeing itt is: I do much long to know
the safe arrivall oft the 10 last packetts, & hope they will give good content: as for more
laus I am not to forward, & shall follow yd advise not haveing as yett above £140
ready bought though al ready sevenall go away & will not leave theim goods at the
formar price, so I am of opinion that itt will vise, seeng wee can nott meet such
quanthes penniwerths as a month sence wee did yett be confident no endeavour is
wanting to romote yd. intrest, & to imploy yd mony well
